T1  - The Management Clinic: Meeting the Challenge of Relevancy in Management Education
AU  - Badawy, M. K.
Y1  - 1976/10/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1976.4396839
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1976.4396839
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 129
EP  - 133
VL  - 1
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article the author discusses the status of management education by examining what is being taught, areas that need to be explored, areas that may be problematic and suggesting possible solutions to these problems. The author notes that while this article offers suggestions and innovations in management education, it is not a model for a management curriculum. The author notes that the main problem associated with management education is the growing divide between academics and practitioners. This divide has resulted in the education becoming largely theoretical without enough focus on real world applications. The author makes several suggestions for how to bridge this gap noting that students, schools and the business community all stand to benefit from this change.
AB  - In this article the author discusses the status of management education by examining what is being taught, areas that need to be explored, areas that may be problematic and suggesting possible solutions to these problems. The author notes that while this article offers suggestions and innovations in management education, it is not a model for a management curriculum. The author notes that the main problem associated with management education is the growing divide between academics and practitioners. This divide has resulted in the education becoming largely theoretical without enough focus on real world applications. The author makes several suggestions for how to bridge this gap noting that students, schools and the business community all stand to benefit from this change.
