TY  - JOUR
T1  - Business Games Have Failed
AU  - Neuhauser, John J.
Y1  - 1976/10/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1976.4396631
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1976.4396631
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 124
EP  - 129
VL  - 1
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The author discusses the use of simulation games in the business world and examines their success. He notes that while these methods are being touted as an educational innovation, there is no real evidence to back up that actual success of these games. He suggests that developers of these computer simulation methods need to pay greater attention to the design, administration and testing of these games in order for them to gain any measurable credibility. He contends that users should gain knowledge of principals when they play these games as well as knowledge of how these principals operate in the real world. This would require a grasp on the social dynamics of the business world and would help prepare students for the decision making processes they will encounter in the field.
AB  - The author discusses the use of simulation games in the business world and examines their success. He notes that while these methods are being touted as an educational innovation, there is no real evidence to back up that actual success of these games. He suggests that developers of these computer simulation methods need to pay greater attention to the design, administration and testing of these games in order for them to gain any measurable credibility. He contends that users should gain knowledge of principals when they play these games as well as knowledge of how these principals operate in the real world. This would require a grasp on the social dynamics of the business world and would help prepare students for the decision making processes they will encounter in the field.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1976.4396631
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1976.4396631
